It appears there's little point in the 30+ billion parameter models these days. With fine tuning, 13B LLaMa-based models seem to largely match or beat the bigger ones. And I'm not hearing about 65B parameter LLaMa at all anymore.

With 4-bit GPTQ, a 13B model works just fine on a "normal" consumer GPU. The weird thing about GPTQ is that it actually seems to improve the performance of at least some models, which kind of blows my mind.

The number of fine-tuned models has exploded, the same way Stable Diffusion models have.

Also, there seems to be an LLM version of Rule 34: if it exists, there's an LLM that can write porn about it.

The way "censorship" works is that the fine-tuning datasets give examples of "illegal" questions (like how to build a pipe bomb, say), and a "canned" response, something like "I can't help you do anything illegal or that might hurt someone." The problem with this approach is that it doesn't actually work; it's easy to "prompt engineer" one's way around, because the information is still in the model. You just have to follow another "route" to get to it.

As an example, instead of directly asking how to build a pipe bomb, ask your chatbot to write a movie scene in which a terrorist builds a pipe bomb. Since the "censored" training example matches the original question, and not the general concept of building a pipe bomb.

There are ways to actually censor models and remove certain concepts entirely. The problem is that they damage the model. And I don't mean in some weird twisted "if it's not the average view of the Internet it's a lie" kind of way. Because we don't understand how the models actually represent information, removing a concept will harm the model's understanding of other, potentially unrelated, concepts.

I need a day away from the news and social media today. I‚Äôm privileged that I can do that, so it‚Äôll be cats, reading fiction, maybe some TV.

Yesterday journalists were shown footage of the Hamas attack from Oct 7, taken from body cams etc. (that they live-streamed themselves in some cases), showing the horrific nature of the deliberate attack on civilians. I won‚Äôt go into detail but you can read about it.

1/6

#Israel #Palestine #Gaza #Hamas

The response I‚Äôve seen in reaction to early reports from these journalists is, ‚ÄúRelease the footage because I don‚Äôt believe it‚Äôs real!‚Äù; ‚ÄúThe world has to see!‚Äù

I hope they don‚Äôt release the footage because we don‚Äôt need video of the massacre spread even more to traumatise the relatives, friends, or even just Jews even more than now. And I don‚Äôt think it would make a *jot* of difference.

2/6

#Israel #Palestine #Gaza #Hamas

People would still believe it‚Äôs created by AI, that it‚Äôs just invented propaganda, that the ‚ÄòZionists‚Äô attacked themselves (I‚Äôve seen this claim already). People were already out on the streets celebrating the ‚Äòresistance‚Äô before the first seven-day mourning period was over, or barely even begun.

[much for the footage is already out there anyway if sick people really want to see it].

3/6

#Israel #Palestine #Gaza #Hamas

It‚Äôs too much. Whatever you think about the current response of the Israeli government‚Äîwhich of course will have been predicted by Hamas and the Iranian backers‚Äîthe Oct 7 attack is indefensible, and I hope people call it out because right now it seems to have been totally forgotten.

4/6

#Israel #Palestine #Gaza #Hamas

I will add this. I don‚Äôt agree with the military response (for humanitarian reasons and also because I can‚Äôt see a long-term plan) but I can understand it. Reporting on the awful situation in Gaza often fails to mention that Hamas is still sending rockets to civilian areas in Israel every day. I hope that at least a functioning humanitarian corridor can be created that *somehow* can assure that Hamas doesn‚Äôt control any aid that goes in.

5/6

#Israel #Palestine #Gaza #Hamas

Finally, everybody seems to be an expert right now on international law and military strategy, but terms like ‚Äògenocide‚Äô have legal definitions along with ‚Äòproportionality‚Äô. If you‚Äôre going to argue that Israel should follow international law then read up on it. Which laws? Which laws contractict those laws? What is ‚Äòbinding‚Äô and what isn‚Äôt and in what context? Educate yourself. You have that privilege.

6/6

#Israel #Palestine #Gaza #Hamas

well that was quite the turnaround! I wasn't expecting much after the decidedly mid first episode, but by the final scenes, it easily matched the original show's high points.

honestly, there's so much that I love about this season, but my favorite had to be Annette's character - a slave-turned-freedom-fighter who, rightfully, views the coddled, brash white revolutionaries with a healthy bit of condescension even as she's largely resigned to playing by their rules. (and, honestly, just having a show that acknowledges the Haitian revolution at all is fucking amazing.) in all, her and Edouard's story is the core of the show in my mind, with Richter's rather bog-standard (albeit well-done) Hero's Journey playing second fiddle.

anyway, I really hope the next season continues focusing on Annette and Edouard instead of shoving them aside now that Alucard is back in the picture.

I've got the initial HTML rendered. Because it's acyclic, a graph can be visualized as a table-of-contents style tree with repeating nodes. Each one is a jumplink to a "card" later on in the page with all the metadata associated with it, as well as jump links to the parent/child nodes.

Currently in the middle of automating the process of automatically generating static HTML for all the subgraphs in the system. Right now, they are all separate and self contained, but the idea is to eventually get them cross-talking together across namespaces.

The dagzet command language feels pretty good. I'm getting faster at transcribing handwritten graphs. Dogfooding right away has been helpful, as it has allowed me to discover small tweaks and shorthands to speed up this process.

So, in the olden times (300+ yrs ago, IIRC) in Germany, there was this thing happening in a circus ring of sorts‚Ä¶ a boarded up circle with seats around it.

And what people would do was gather there and take a cat.

They would then tar the cat, set it on fire, throw it in the ring and then proceed to watch and cheer while the cat ran around the ring, screaming and dying a horrible, agonizing death.

This was considered peak entertainment.

Commonly named Sapphire Ornamental or Peacock Tarantula, Poecilotheria metallica is the only blue species of her genus. It is found in the deciduous forest of Andhra Pradesh, in central southern India. It is arboreal, living in holes of tall trees where it makes asymmetric funnel webs, and may live communally when territory is limited. Popular in the pet trade (@Bwee and I have one named Dory üòÅ), it is an Old World tarantula, with speed and potent venom, so not the best choice for beginner keepers.

The dismantling of the Australian COVID-19 case reporting is hiding the scale (or even existence) of the current wave of community transmission sweeping across the country.

From the health.gov.au data (faithfully extracted by @dbRaevn) here are 4 key metrics, on a log scale to compare waves:
- Cases (reported from PCR & RAT tests)
- Hospitalised cases
- Aged Care Staff cases
- PBS scripts (for oral treatments)

Its fairly clear that they each move up in down in close synchronisation as the waves and troughs have occurred. Each metric has stayed within fairly consistent ranges, apart from Cases which in a steady decline, making historical comparisons irrelevant.

I think the most consistent is Aged Care Staff cases, where there is still mostly mandating of testing and reporting. I do expect that to be eroding slowly to become less accurate, but it's probably the best we have.

#COVID19 #Australia @auscovid19
